IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
***Body-Worn Camera and In-Car camera operational.***

- Defendant: Santos Chagala Silverio 
- Defendant's Date of Birth: 11/01/1988
- Time of Arrest: 2111
- DUI #: 23-038
- PBT: .292
-Intoxometer: Refusal

TRAINING

- Trained in administering Standardized Field Sobriety Tests (SFSTs) by the Maryland State Police and National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA).
- Certified to operate and administer the Preliminary Breath Test (PBT).
- Trained in Advanced Roadside Impaired Driving Enforcement (ARIDE) by the Maryland State Police and National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA).

VEHICLE IN MOTION (PHASE 1)

On Friday, April 7, 2023, at approximately 2047 hours, I, Trooper Gernatt #7248, was on routine patrol southbound Interstate 95 in the area of the 81.1-mile marker, in marked patrol vehicle M-48. At that time, I observed a blue Toyota Camry bearing Maryland registration: "6FF8223", being operated with an inoperable taillight and tag light. I followed the blue Toyota for three tenths of a mile and observed the blue Toyota weaving from left to right within lane three. I activated my emergency equipment and conducted a traffic stop on the blue Toyota. 

PERSONAL CONTACT (PHASE 2)

I made a passenger-side approach and made contact with the operator, who was the sole occupant of the blue Toyota. The operator was later identified by his Mexican Passport as Santos Chagala Silverio (Hispanic male DOB 11/01/1988). Before Silverio rolled down his window, he placed a blue medical face mask on his face, covering both his mouth and nose. I advised Silverio who I was, and the reason for the traffic stop. While speaking with Silverio, I observed that his eyes were glassy and bloodshot. I detected the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from the vehicle. I asked Silverio how much alcohol he had that night, and he replied "Just a beer". Silverio stated that he had one Bud Light two hours ago. 

I requested Silverio to perform Standardized Field Sobriety Tests, which he agreed.

PRE-ARREST SCREENING (PHASE 3)

The evaluation was performed in front of the blue Toyota, on the right shoulder of Interstate 95. The surface was dry, level, and free from any obvious debris. The lighting conditions were the street lamps of Interstate 95, and my flashlight. Silverio appeared to be in good physical condition and did not display any visible injuries, limps, or limb ailments. After separating Silverio from the vehicle, I still detected the odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from his breath.

-    Silverio does not wear contacts or glasses 
-    Silverio advised that he has not taken any drugs or medications
-    Silverio offered no statements that would prevent him from walking and balancing. 

HORIZONTAL GAZE NYSTAGMUS (4/6 CLUES OBSERVED)

The first test given was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus test. The tip of my pen was the stimulus and held approximately 12 inches from Silverio's eyes, slightly above eye level. Silverio was instructed to look at the stimulus and to follow the stimulus with only his eyes. Silverio's eyes were equal in size and showed equal tracking and no resting Nystagmus was observed. 

- Lack of Smooth Pursuit – Present in both eyes
- Distinct and Sustained Nystagmus at Maximum Deviation – Present in both eyes
- Onset of Nystagmus Prior to 45 Degrees – Not Present – Silverio was reminded to look at the tip of my pen multiple times. Silverio was looking straight ahead and at me. 
- Vertical Gaze Nystagmus – Silverio followed the pen with his eyes and head
      *Eyes dilated*
Note: Silverio was reminded to look at the tip of my pen for a total of eight times. Silverio failed to follow directions by looking at me, and looking straight ahead instead of following the stimulus. When Silverio was reminded of the instructions for the test, he stated "I know," and "I'm sorry.” 

WALK AND TURN (4/8 CLUES OBSERVED)

Prior to Silverio performing the test, I explained and demonstrated how the test should be conducted. Silverio was instructed to place his right foot directly in front of his left foot, touching heel to toe, and his hands down at his side. Silverio was then instructed to remain in that position. Silverio was instructed to take nine (9) heel-to-toe steps in a straight line, counting out loud. On the ninth step, Silverio was instructed to complete a series of small steps around his lead foot. Silverio was again explained and demonstrated that the second series of nine (9) steps were to be completed in the exact same manner as the first series of steps. Silverio was instructed to look down at his feet, and count his steps out loud, while keeping his hands down at his sides. I asked Silverio if he understood the test, and Silverio acknowledged that he did. (Footwear: Silverio was wearing slides. I asked him if he would rather perform test in slides or barefoot. Silverio advised that he had shoes in the trunk. I allowed Silverio to change into his high-top basketball shoes.)

Instructional Stage: 
-    Cannot keep balance during the instructional stage. 

Walking Stage (1st Nine):
-    Stopped while walking (Step #6)
-    Stepped off the line (Step #6)
-    Incorrect number of steps (12 steps)

Turn: 
-    Not completed satisfactorily.

Walking Stage (2nd Nine):
-    Not completed, Silverio casually walked back to the starting position

Note: Once Silverio completed the first series of steps, he walked back to the starting position and took thirty steps before I told him to stop.

ONE LEG STAND (2/4 CLUES OBSERVED)

Prior to performing the test, I explained and demonstrated how the test should be performed. Silverio was instructed to stand with his feet together and hands down at his sides. Silverio was to raise the foot of his choice off the ground approximately 6 inches, as demonstrated. While Silverio's leg was raised he was to keep his leg straight, watch his raised foot, and count out loud by the thousands (one thousand-one, one thousand-two, one thousand-three, etc.) and to continue until told to stop. I asked Silverio if he understood the test, and he stated "Yeah, I understand.” Silverio stated, "I'm going to try”. (Footwear: high-top basketball shoes). Silverio chose to raise his right foot.

Instructional Stage: 
-    Nothing observed
Balance and Counting Stage:
-    Put foot down (three times)
-    Uses arms for balance

Preliminary Breath Test (PBT)

Silverio submitted to a preliminary breath test administered by Trooper First Class Sawyer #7129. Silverio’s results were a .292 (serial #116098).

ARREST

Based on the following, I had reason to believe Silverio was driving a motor vehicle under the influence:
- I observed a blue Toyota Camry weaving within its lane.
- In an attempt to mask the odor of an alcoholic beverage, Silverio placed a medical facemask over his mouth prior to my initial approach.
- Silverio admitted to consuming one Bud Light two hours before my interaction with him. 
- The strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from Silverio's breath and person. 
- My observed signs of impairment as Silverio performed field sobriety tests.
- PBT result of .292.

I arrested Silverio at approximately 2111 hours for driving under the influence of alcohol. 

Silverio was placed in the front passenger seat of my patrol vehicle and transported to the Maryland State Police JFK Highway Barrack for processing. While in my patrol vehicle, I played the Spanish audio version of the DR-15 from the Maryland Motor Vehicle Administration's website. Upon arrival at the barrack, I gave Silverio a copy of the DR-15.  Silverio signed the DR-15 at approximately 2159 hours refusing to submit to an Intoximeter Test. 

INTOXOMETER RESULT: REFUSAL

Once the paperwork was completed, Silverio was transported and released to the custody of Harford County IPC. 

All events occurred in Harford County, Maryland.
